**Redesigning the Accelerator**

I'm currently focused on the UI update for the Accelerator component. I'm swapping out the name "加速器" for "TIME WARP // 时间流速," as requested. The design direction is sci-fi, so I'm thinking about how to integrate this aesthetic into the visual style of the control.


**Developing the Cyberpunk Aesthetic**

I've been honing in on the cyberpunk, HUD style for the accelerator UI.  My focus is on neon blue hues, angled geometries, and dynamic lighting. The goal is to evoke the feeling of a warp drive console.  I'm now thinking about energy bars as continuous lattices with holographic textures and speed-reactive color shifts from cyan to red. I plan to modify `components/UIOverlay.tsx` accordingly, replacing discrete buttons with this new design.


**Conceptualizing Speed Bars**

I'm now thinking the speed control should be a visual power meter. We can still allow clicking to set the speed. Each segment will act as a "cell" or "bar," with `simulationSpeed` controlling the number lit. I've designed a color gradient: low speeds are blue/cyan, medium speeds are green/yellow, and high speeds are red/orange. I've begun work on the style for the `warp-container` and `warp-scanline` components in `UIOverlay.tsx`, and I'm ready to prototype and test!


**Finalizing Warp Bar Animation**

I've got the animation for the warp bar pretty much locked down. I've integrated a shining effect that really sells the feeling of acceleration, and it's looking great. I've also added some final touches to the text style, making it truly cyberpunk. I think it is nearly ready for review!


**Implementing Speed Configuration**

I've been working on the speed configuration. I've built a speed configuration array using Tailwind colors to allow the system to switch between different speeds. I've also implemented conditional styling to indicate the active and selected speeds.


**Refining the Glow Effect**

I've been improving the glow effect. I am dynamically setting the shadow color based on the speed intensity. The colors transition from cyan at low speeds to yellow and eventually to red at higher speeds. This is providing excellent visual feedback and enhancing the overall cyberpunk aesthetic.  I am pleased with how this is turning out!


**Connecting UI with States**

I'm now integrating the visual feedback from the speed configuration into the UI. I'm focusing on ensuring the styling, particularly the glow effects, accurately reflects the current speed state.  My primary focus is on ensuring a smooth transition between speeds and visually representing the intensity.
```tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { useSimulationStore } from '@/store';
import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge';

interface UIOverlayProps {
  // Define any props this component might need.
}

const UIOverlay: React.FC<UIOverlayProps> = () => {
  const [showMenu, setShowMenu] = useState(false);
  const [isWarpActive, setIsWarpActive] = useState(false);
  const [isWarpScanlineVisible, setIsWarpScanlineVisible] = useState(false);
  const [warpLevel, setWarpLevel] = useState(0);

  const simulationSpeed = useSimulationStore((state) => state.simulationSpeed);
  const setSimulationSpeed = useSimulationStore((state) => state.setSimulationSpeed);
  const isPaused = useSimulationStore((state) => state.isPaused);
  const setIsPaused = useSimulationStore((state) => state.setIsPaused);

  const handleToggleMenu = () => {
    setShowMenu(!showMenu);
  };

  const speedOptions = [
    { label: '0%', value: 0 },
    { label: '80%', value: 0.8 },
    { label: '100%', value: 1 },
    { label: '0', value: 0 },
    { label: '100%', value: 1 },
    { label: '0', value: 0 },
    { label: '20%', value: 0.2 }
  ];

  const warpSpeedColors = [
    'bg-blue-200',
    'bg-cyan-300',
    'bg-green-400',
    'bg-yellow-500',
    'bg-orange-600',
    'bg-red-700'
  ];

  useEffect(() => {
    setIsWarpActive(simulationSpeed > 1 || simulationSpeed < 0.8 && simulationSpeed > 0);
  }, [simulationSpeed]);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (isWarpActive) {
      setIsWarpScanlineVisible(true);
      const timer = setTimeout(() => {
        setIsWarpScanlineVisible(false);
      }, 1000);
      return () => clearTimeout(timer);
    } else {
      setIsWarpScanlineVisible(false);
    }
  }, [isWarpActive]);

  const handleSpeedSelect = (value: number) => {
    if (value === 0 && isPaused) {
      setIsPaused(false)
    }
    setSimulationSpeed(value);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    const warpLevel = Math.max(0, Math.min(100, simulationSpeed * 100 / 2));
    setWarpLevel(warpLevel);
  }, [simulationSpeed]);

  return (
    <div className="absolute inset-0 flex flex-col items-center justify-between pointer-events-none">
      <div className="flex items-center justify-between w-full p-4">
        {/* Top-left Menu Icon (Pause/Play) */}
        <button
          className="p-2 rounded-full bg-black/50 text-white hover:bg-black/70 transition-colors pointer-events-auto"
          onClick={() => {
            setIsPaused(!isPaused);
            if (simulationSpeed === 0 && !isPaused) {
              setSimulationSpeed(1)
            }
          }}
        >
          {isPaused ? (
            <svg
              xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              className="h-6 w-6"
              fill="none"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              stroke="currentColor"
            >
              <path strokeLinecap="round" strokeLinejoin="round" strokeWidth={2} d="M10 9v6m4-6v6m7-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />


**Updating the UI's Core**

I'm now focusing on a complete overhaul of the `UIOverlay` component.  I'm replacing the incomplete code with a fully functional design that incorporates the TIME WARP aesthetics, including a dynamic speed display and controls. The aim is to create an immersive, cyberpunk-inspired control panel that responds visually to changes in speed and state.

